<h2 id="what-is-poemaday">What is poemADAY</h2>

<p>Poemaday <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">(poem a day/a poem a day)</code> well, is not a very creative and out of the box name but it is what the name suggests. I built this blog to post one poem every day (written by someone else) and talk about it. I know, what a drab! But I assure you, itâ€™s nothing like â€œYouTube reaction videosâ€. My plan is not to leech off of other peopleâ€™s art. I simply wish to talk about poems and poets that come from all walks of life. Mainly, I want to focus on <strong>South Asian poets</strong> and then branch off from there.</p>

<h2 id="why-poemaday">Why poemADAY</h2>

<p>To be honest, Iâ€™m not a very honest person (<em>Woah, what a loop</em>). Iâ€™m also not a very bold person. I am meek as far as internet â€œ<strong>speak up/ speak about</strong>â€ goes. While I was growing up, poetry wasnâ€™t taught very religiously in my school, nor did I have parents who give their kids â€œbooksâ€ to read so there was simply no way of discovering poetry. I, along with numerous students in those schools missed out on poetry and somehow it wasnâ€™t the end of the world. Passing on poetry doesnâ€™t limit your chances of becoming an engineer or a doctor, or a lawyer in India. But it caught on with me. Something about the verses irked me. And so, like a little Alice I decided to delve into the wonder pit of poetry and when I came out, I only had lots and lots of strange awe for it.</p>

<p>What was more irksome is how poets all over the world have been writing these very interesting pieces and somehow I didnâ€™t know how to understand them, or even how to consume them. We were simply never taught how to approach strange beings of poetry. So, this blog is a feverish attempt to understand poems by writing about them. What better way to learn something than teaching it (after learning)? Thereâ€™s however a small hiccup. Remember how I said I am not a very bold person? Yes. So, itâ€™s very difficult for me to talk about something that isnâ€™t written by me. Itâ€™s that dreadful imposter syndrome and I want to rise above it. I feel like thereâ€™s a certain way one is supposed to talk and write about things (the internet way) and since Iâ€™ve always felt like a very unintuitive person, I regularly put off that task. But now, I wish to overcome that fear and learn how to write about things, in <strong>my own way</strong>.</p>

<h2 id="therefore-i-assure-you-this-is-the-last-conclusion">Therefore, (I assure you this is the last conclusion)</h2>

<p>So birthed, <strong>poemADAY</strong>. For skimmers, let me just very carefully enlist what poemADAY wants to achieve.</p>

<ol>
  <li>Discover poets from all walks of life</li>
  <li>Learn to understand poetry</li>
  <li>Enjoy reading poetry (thus, develop a reading habit)</li>
  <li>Talk about poetry</li>
  <li>Develop space to express thoughts on poetry</li>
  <li>Make email-friends</li>
  <li>Build community (oh yeah, nothing like the rush that building a community gives no? hahahahahaha, meh)</li>
